WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.760
Have you ever been in need of a tool that you didn't have?

00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:15.080
Imagine that you have this screw that you need to unscrew, but you don't have the right

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:17.280
screwdriver to do that.

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:20.400
So what do you do?

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:21.719
Go to the nearest hardware store.

00:00:21.719 --> 00:00:28.200
You look at the various screwdrivers they have, bigger, smaller, different screw heads.

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:35.000
You pick the one that will match your screw, you bring it home, you unscrew, you're good.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Some time passes.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:42.360
You want to find a table that will match the space between your sofa and the wall.

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:45.520
But you don't have a measuring tape, and you need one.

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:48.080
So what do you do?

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:52.400
You go to the nearest hardware store, look at the various measuring tapes they have.

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:56.119
Longer, shorter, thinner, wider.

00:00:56.119 --> 00:00:59.959
Start wondering why that even matters, but you need to make a decision.

00:00:59.959 --> 00:01:04.919
So you pick one, bring it home, measure, you're good.

00:01:04.919 --> 00:01:06.599
Some time passes.

00:01:06.599 --> 00:01:08.800
You need to hammer a nail.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:12.000
So what do you do?

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:17.760
You start wondering, wouldn't it make sense to buy a complete toolbox instead of assembling

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:21.480
one tool by tool?

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:22.480
My name is Kamil.

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:25.839
I'm a full stack engineer at Appsilon.

00:01:25.839 --> 00:01:29.559
We specialize in building Shiny applications.

00:01:29.559 --> 00:01:35.320
Let me tell you of a typical situation that we faced many times over in our work.

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:41.239
So a client comes to us and asks whether we could build an application for them.

00:01:41.239 --> 00:01:45.879
Using wonderful capabilities of Shiny, we create something within a couple of hours

00:01:45.879 --> 00:01:49.839
that is interactive and impresses the client.

00:01:49.839 --> 00:01:50.839
Contract signed.

00:01:51.199 --> 00:01:52.199
The project starts.

00:01:52.199 --> 00:01:54.040
A couple of weeks pass.

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:56.440
The code base grows 20 times.

00:01:56.440 --> 00:02:02.599
And realize that we are spending a lot of time discussing the code style, where the

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:04.720
opening brackets should be.

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:08.119
We figure that we need some tool that will automatically check this for us.

00:02:08.119 --> 00:02:09.800
We need a linter.

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:12.279
So what do we do?

00:02:12.279 --> 00:02:17.000
We find linter, we configure it properly, we add it to the project, we start linting

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:19.919
our code, we're good.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.119
Some time passes.

00:02:22.119 --> 00:02:28.160
We realize that we touch one place in the application and something else breaks.

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:31.039
So we figure that we should start writing tests.

00:02:31.039 --> 00:02:32.600
We need unit tests.

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:33.600
What do we do?

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:39.039
We find test that, we configure it, we add it to the project, we start writing unit tests.

00:02:39.039 --> 00:02:41.080
We're good.

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:43.160
Some time passes.

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:45.080
And you get the point.

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:48.520
Needs keep arising and we need to keep addressing them.

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:54.919
You start wondering, wouldn't it make sense to start with a complete development toolbox

00:02:54.919 --> 00:02:58.960
instead of assembling one tool by tool?

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:00.279
This goes deeper, though.

00:03:00.279 --> 00:03:05.600
In case of development tools, introducing them later on in the project is typically

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:06.600
more costly.

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:11.199
For example, if you want to add linter when you already have hundreds of linter errors,

00:03:11.199 --> 00:03:13.559
you'll first have to fix them all.

00:03:13.559 --> 00:03:19.160
And that's not only a lot of work, but you need to synchronize it with your team.

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:21.679
But we should take even a wider perspective, though.

00:03:21.679 --> 00:03:23.300
It's not just one project.

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:28.000
It's multiple teams dealing with multiple projects at the same time.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.479
And similar needs arise in each of those projects.

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:34.600
And each team keeps configuring the same tools.

00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:38.699
Wouldn't it be wonderful to have just one universal toolbox?

00:03:38.699 --> 00:03:43.000
All this effort could be directed into really polishing it instead of reinventing the wheel

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:44.440
all the time.

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:50.440
Moreover, in an organization, when you have just one universal toolbox, people get proficient

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:51.759
using it.

00:03:51.759 --> 00:03:56.720
So when you start a new project or move to a different one, everybody's up to speed right

00:03:56.720 --> 00:03:57.720
from the beginning.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:01.660
This can really bring the productivity to a whole new level.

00:04:01.660 --> 00:04:05.520
So you can see what kind of problem we have here.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:08.679
And this is where my personal story begins.

00:04:08.679 --> 00:04:10.300
Right here in the middle.

00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:13.919
So I joined Epsilon two years ago in July.

00:04:13.919 --> 00:04:15.300
It was a hot month.

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:17.059
My birthday was coming.

00:04:17.059 --> 00:04:20.540
It was the last month of our only office being open.

00:04:20.540 --> 00:04:21.540
Pandemic was raging.

00:04:21.540 --> 00:04:24.239
Lots of things were happening.

00:04:24.239 --> 00:04:28.619
So my first project was called Project Patterns.

00:04:28.619 --> 00:04:29.619
What was that?

00:04:29.619 --> 00:04:36.579
Well, technically speaking, it was a Git repository with snippets of code on branches and a related

00:04:36.579 --> 00:04:41.739
Python tool that could be used to combine them into project structure for new and existing

00:04:41.739 --> 00:04:42.739
projects.

00:04:42.739 --> 00:04:43.739
Sounds complicated?

00:04:43.739 --> 00:04:45.779
It was.

00:04:45.779 --> 00:04:48.260
And it was my task to improve it.

00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:51.339
So first of all, I tried to understand the purpose of all this.

00:04:51.339 --> 00:04:56.500
And I started researching what we tried to do about this in the past.

00:04:56.500 --> 00:04:59.100
And it turned out that we did a lot.

00:04:59.100 --> 00:05:02.500
Like years before already, we had discussion groups.

00:05:02.500 --> 00:05:07.100
And we had a repository of code snippets that could be reused to some extent.

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:10.299
Directly before Project Patterns, we had something called...

00:05:10.299 --> 00:05:14.799
We had a setup involving RStudio in Docker and a related bash tool that could be used

00:05:14.799 --> 00:05:17.440
to automate some of the things.

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:23.739
So I realized that already many people before me tried to solve these problems that we had.

00:05:23.739 --> 00:05:25.619
And I had a week to improve that.

00:05:25.619 --> 00:05:29.339
You can guess that I didn't manage to fix everything within that week.

00:05:29.339 --> 00:05:33.859
But for the following two years, we kept improving what we had.

00:05:33.859 --> 00:05:39.359
For example, we went through a phase of simplification, where instead of having all this complex set

00:05:39.359 --> 00:05:43.380
of tools, we created just a simple, shiny template.

00:05:43.380 --> 00:05:47.899
A Git repository that could be cloned and used as a basis for your project.

00:05:47.899 --> 00:05:49.540
We also researched other tools.

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:51.739
For example, we took a look at Golem.

00:05:51.739 --> 00:05:54.140
We tried to learn how it differs from our approach.

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:55.619
We tried to learn from it.

00:05:55.619 --> 00:05:58.700
We considered whether we could just use it.

00:05:59.339 --> 00:06:04.339
For two years, we kept addressing needs as they were arising, resolving issues as they

00:06:04.339 --> 00:06:05.339
were surfacing.

00:06:05.339 --> 00:06:10.459
And finally, in the year 2022, we started feeling that we have something that we want

00:06:10.459 --> 00:06:12.299
to share with the world.

00:06:12.299 --> 00:06:15.100
And thus, Rhino was born.

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:17.420
No, not just Rhino.

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:23.459
Rhino, the free and open-source R package, which we announced in May this year during

00:06:23.459 --> 00:06:25.940
Appsilon Shiny Conference.

00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:28.100
So it's an R package.

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:29.100
Means it has functions.

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:32.260
For example, this Rhino init function.

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:34.899
It creates a new Rhino project for you.

00:06:34.899 --> 00:06:38.380
So what do you get inside?

00:06:38.380 --> 00:06:43.980
Perhaps the most obvious part is the full project structure of files and directories.

00:06:43.980 --> 00:06:49.339
So we have places for configuration, source files, dependencies, tests.

00:06:49.339 --> 00:06:51.459
Everything is covered from the beginning.

00:06:51.459 --> 00:06:55.820
So let's take a deeper look at some of those.

00:06:56.700 --> 00:07:00.179
Any project will need other R packages to do its job.

00:07:00.179 --> 00:07:05.899
And it's very important to be explicit about what these other packages are and what versions

00:07:05.899 --> 00:07:07.019
you need.

00:07:07.019 --> 00:07:11.500
If you are not explicit about that, you might find that when you try to launch a project

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:14.420
after a couple of months, it doesn't work.

00:07:14.420 --> 00:07:15.420
Why?

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:16.420
Who knows?

00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:19.579
Maybe some package got updated and it broke.

00:07:19.579 --> 00:07:24.820
If you have an explicit list of dependencies, the chances that it will just work are much

00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:25.820
higher.

00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:29.260
And we have R package to deal with this.

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:34.059
For a similar issue but related to the R sources themselves, we have the box package.

00:07:34.059 --> 00:07:41.179
This one allows you to use Python-style imports at the top of each file so that for each file

00:07:41.179 --> 00:07:47.980
it is immediately obvious what packages, functions, and other files it needs.

00:07:47.980 --> 00:07:52.899
So moving on to the quality of R code.

00:07:52.899 --> 00:07:55.619
We have three packages which deal with that.

00:07:55.619 --> 00:07:59.179
For writing tests, we have test that package.

00:07:59.179 --> 00:08:03.940
Then we have lint R, which can be used to automatically test the style of your codes

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:07.040
and also detect some errors that you might have.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:11.859
And we have the styler package, which is able to fix many of those problems automatically.

00:08:11.859 --> 00:08:15.779
All these tools can be run using Rhino functions out of the box.

00:08:15.779 --> 00:08:17.619
You don't need to configure anything.

00:08:17.619 --> 00:08:24.540
Just do, for example, Rhino lint R, and you get your code linted.

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:29.859
So in enterprise settings, typically you will have some needs that will be quite common.

00:08:29.859 --> 00:08:32.419
For example, one of them is logging.

00:08:32.419 --> 00:08:36.780
It is very important to output good log messages from your application.

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:40.659
If it breaks, for example, in production, this kind of log messages can really help

00:08:40.659 --> 00:08:43.099
you to find what the issue is.

00:08:43.099 --> 00:08:46.219
And we have the logger package, which deals with that.

00:08:46.219 --> 00:08:50.140
Then you typically will have more than one environment.

00:08:50.140 --> 00:08:53.539
You will have the local one when you develop the application.

00:08:53.539 --> 00:08:58.659
Then you will have staging where you will be testing it before pushing it to production.

00:08:58.659 --> 00:09:02.700
And to manage the differences between these different environments, we have the config

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:05.179
package.

00:09:05.179 --> 00:09:11.260
Now in any big project, we realize that sooner or later we need JavaScript.

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:15.900
We need to customize the application beyond what's provided by our packages.

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:19.979
And we figured, why not use the state-of-the-art tech for that?

00:09:19.979 --> 00:09:24.219
So for JavaScript, we will run your code through Babel and Webpack.

00:09:24.219 --> 00:09:29.559
This to ensure that you can use the latest features without worrying about browser support.

00:09:29.559 --> 00:09:35.080
We have SLint that you can use to check the quality of your JavaScript code and also fix

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:37.659
many of the errors automatically.

00:09:37.659 --> 00:09:42.500
While these things need Node.js to be installed on your machine, when using it from Rhino,

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:47.179
you will just call the package functions, build.js, lint.js.

00:09:47.179 --> 00:09:52.140
Now similarly, we typically need to add some custom styling.

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:53.940
And we chose SAS to do that.

00:09:53.940 --> 00:09:58.719
It's an extension for the CSS language, which allows you to structure your code in a more

00:09:58.719 --> 00:10:01.080
maintainable and better way.

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:06.500
And again, here, to compile your SAS into something understandable by the browser, we

00:10:06.500 --> 00:10:10.299
use the state-of-the-art latest implementation of SAS.

00:10:10.299 --> 00:10:16.099
We also have style lint, which is able to lint your style files automatically.

00:10:16.099 --> 00:10:19.460
Now what else do you need in a big project?

00:10:19.460 --> 00:10:21.900
Well, certainly more testing.

00:10:21.900 --> 00:10:27.700
And as we already are using Node.js, we are using also Cypress for end-to-end testing

00:10:27.700 --> 00:10:29.859
of your application.

00:10:29.859 --> 00:10:34.380
This framework allows you to launch your whole application, interact with it, like press

00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:38.820
buttons, type text, and then verify if it behaved as expected.

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:42.500
For example, that some text appeared or a window got opened.

00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:49.419
So again, this can be used simply by running a function of the package called test end-to-end.

00:10:49.419 --> 00:10:54.099
And finally, as a cherry on top, automation.

00:10:54.099 --> 00:10:58.219
All these tools are useless if you are not actually running them.

00:10:58.219 --> 00:11:03.380
And if it's not happening automatically, sooner or later, you will probably forget about it.

00:11:03.380 --> 00:11:11.619
So if you use GitHub, Rhino comes with a working out-of-the-box setup for GitHub Actions.

00:11:11.619 --> 00:11:16.979
These will run all the linters, unit tests, end-to-end tests for you automatically once

00:11:16.979 --> 00:11:20.260
you initialize your project.

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:24.340
All right, so to summarize, what is Rhino?

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:30.059
Well, certainly you can think of it as this complete development toolbox with all those

00:11:30.059 --> 00:11:33.419
things that I've just listed and mentioned.

00:11:33.419 --> 00:11:35.260
But it's more than that.

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:37.940
We call it a framework.

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:44.260
And if you know other frameworks for Python or Ruby on Rails, we took a slightly different

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:45.659
angle here.

00:11:45.659 --> 00:11:52.500
While you do get the project structure, packages to use, and basic structure for your application,

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:56.859
we also have all these tools around it for ensuring the quality of your code.

00:11:56.859 --> 00:12:02.380
So we can think of Rhino as a framework, but for the whole development process.

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:07.140
Then Rhino is certainly the absolute way to do things.

00:12:07.140 --> 00:12:12.619
It is an opinionated framework based on years of experience that we have in building Shiny

00:12:12.619 --> 00:12:13.619
applications.

00:12:13.619 --> 00:12:18.859
It is not the only way to do things, but it is the way that we believe in and that we

00:12:18.859 --> 00:12:20.539
recommend.

00:12:20.539 --> 00:12:24.219
And finally, Rhino is great for enterprise.

00:12:24.219 --> 00:12:28.059
While you can certainly use it in your next proof of concept project that you will show

00:12:28.059 --> 00:12:35.020
to nobody, its benefits really start to shine in organizations when you have this one universal

00:12:35.020 --> 00:12:37.539
toolbox which everybody can use.

00:12:37.539 --> 00:12:42.219
It really can bring your productivity to a new level.

00:12:42.219 --> 00:12:49.940
So I hope this got you a bit interested in Rhino, perhaps maybe even somewhat excited.

00:12:49.940 --> 00:12:54.700
So if that's the case, all you need to do is to go to our website.

00:12:54.700 --> 00:12:58.820
It contains an extensive documentation for the package, as we believe it is an essential

00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:01.219
part of a framework like this.

00:13:01.219 --> 00:13:06.700
So thank you for listening, and I encourage you to use Rhino in your next project.

00:13:07.299 --> 00:13:08.299
Thank you.

00:13:08.299 --> 00:13:09.299
Thank you.

00:13:09.299 --> 00:13:09.299


